{"parse":{"title":"Corelative","pageid":2008422,"revid":839321969,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Correlative</b> (\"corelative,\" UK spelling) is the term adopted by <a href=\"/wiki/Wesley_Newcomb_Hohfeld\" title=\"Wesley Newcomb Hohfeld\">Wesley Newcomb Hohfeld</a> to describe the philosophical relationships between fundamental legal concepts in <a href=\"/wiki/Jurisprudence\" title=\"Jurisprudence\">jurisprudence</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Hohfeldian_analysis\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Hohfeldian analysis</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#In_practice\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">In practice</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Hohfeldian_analysis\">Hohfeldian analysis</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Corelative&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Hohfeldian analysis\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Hohfeld was concerned that there was some ambiguity in the explanation of the similarities and differences between concepts in law. Hence, with the focus on the nature of <i>rights</i>, he proposed a system of analysis based on \"jural correlatives\" and \"jural opposites\". A correlative is where two concepts are <a href=\"/wiki/Logically_consistent\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Logically consistent\">logically consistent</a> and the one necessarily implies the other. When two concepts are Hohfeldian opposites (technically, logical contradictions), they are mutually exclusive.\n</p><p>Thus, if A has a right with regard to B, an analysis of their relationship from B's point of view must imply that B has a duty to A. An owner of land may hold four distinct entitlements: rights, privileges, powers, and immunities. Hohfeld linked each entitlement to a corelative and its opposite:\n</p>\n<table style=\"width:250px; height:200px\" border=\"1\">\n\n<tbody><tr>\n<td><b>Elements</b>\n</td>\n<td><b>Correlatives</b>\n</td>\n<td><b>Opposites</b>\n</td></tr>\n<tr style=\"height:100px\">\n<td>Right\n</td>\n<td style=\"width:250px\">Duty\n</td>\n<td>No Right\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Privilege or Liberty\n</td>\n<td>No Right\n</td>\n<td>Duty\n</td></tr>\n<tr style=\"height:100px\">\n<td>Power\n</td>\n<td style=\"width:250px\">Liability\n</td>\n<td>Disability\n</td></tr>\n<tr style=\"height:100px\">\n<td>Immunity\n</td>\n<td style=\"width:250px\">Disability\n</td>\n<td>Liability\n</td></tr>\n\n</tbody></table>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"In_practice\">In practice</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Corelative&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: In practice\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Jurists such as <a href=\"/wiki/Scepticism_in_law\" title=\"Scepticism in law\">Dias</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Wesley_Newcomb_Hohfeld#Hohfeldian_analysis\" title=\"Wesley Newcomb Hohfeld\">Hohfeld</a> have declared that rights and duties are <i>jural corelatives</i>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> which means that if someone has a right, <i>someone else</i> owes a duty to him. This reasoning of Dias' was used in <i><a href=\"/wiki/Murphy_v_Brentwood_DC\" title=\"Murphy v Brentwood DC\">Murphy v Brentwood District Council</a></i> (1991) to disapprove  <a href=\"/wiki/Alfred_Denning\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Alfred Denning\">Lord Denning</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Master_of_the_Rolls\" title=\"Master of the Rolls\">MR</a>'s judgment in <i><a href=\"/wiki/Dutton_v_Bognor_Regis_UDC\" title=\"Dutton v Bognor Regis UDC\">Dutton v Bognor Regis Urban District Council</a></i> (1972).<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Corelative&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Civil_rights\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Civil rights\">Civil rights</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Corelative&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Dias, Reginald Walter Michael (1976). <i>Jurisprudence</i>. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/2668655\">2668655</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Jurisprudence&amp;rft.date=1976&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F2668655&amp;rft.aulast=Dias&amp;rft.aufirst=Reginald+Walter+Michael&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACorelative\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Denning had argued, wrongly, that when a local council has a right to inspect a building under construction, the council has a corresponding duty of care to \"inspect properly\".</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<ul><li>Hohfeld, W. N. <i>Fundamental Legal Conceptions as Applied in Judicial Reasoning</i>, ed. by W.W. Cook (1919); reprint, New Haven, CT: Yale University Press, (1964).</li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1323\nCached time: 20180909080127\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.072 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.086 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 125/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 1284/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 74/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1256/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.026/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.34 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   67.287      1 Template:Reflist\n100.00%   67.287      1 -total\n 83.65%   56.287      1 Template:Cite_book\n  2.84%    1.912      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:2008422-0!canonical and timestamp 20180909080126 and revision id 839321969\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","*":"Philosophy_of_law"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Human_rights"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Alfred Denning"},{"ns":0,"e